I"Ÿ<p>It has been a long and sedentary lockdown, and I have been greatly missing my rock climbing adventures of last winter and summer.
I have been interested in backpacking in a very long time, and since Iâ€™m not currently in contact with anyone else who rock climbs,
it is the most adventurous outdoor activity that I can actually do. For my first ever trip, I decided to head to one of my favorite
places, Yosemite National Park. The permiting system was easier than I expected: choose a trailhead, make sure itâ€™s not reserved for
your date, and fill out a simple form. I opted for the McGurk meadows trailhead, and planned to hike to and camp at Dewey Point with Mia.</p>

<p>On Wednesday, we got up early and drove out to the park. I decided to head through the south entrance, as I wanted to check out the giant
sequoias of the Mariposa grove and show Mia the full experience of tunnel view.</p>

<p><img src="/assets/images/dew/mariposa.jpg" alt="Fallen sequoia in the Mariposa grove. Biggest trees I have ever seen, but not necessarily worth the walk given limited time to explore Yosemite" width="500" /><br />
